SIMPLE: entail
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Entail
<hw>En*tail"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>entaile</ets> carving, OF. <ets>entaille</ets>, F., an incision,
fr. <ets>entailler</ets> to cut away; pref. <ets>en-</ets> (L.
<ets>in</ets>) + <ets>tailler</ets> to cut; LL. <ets>feudum
talliatum</ets> a fee entailed, i. e., curtailed or limited. See
<er>Tail</er> limitation, <er>Tailor</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That
which is entailed.</def> Hence: <fld>(Law)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>An
estate in fee entailed, or limited in descent to a particular class of
issue.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The rule by which the descent is
fixed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A power of breaking the ancient <qex>entails</qex>, and of
alienating their estates.</q> <rj><qau>Hume.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Delicately carved ornamental work; intaglio.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧A work of rich <xex>entail</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Entail</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Entail
<hw>En*tail"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Entailed</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Entailing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>entailen</ets> to
carve, OF. <ets>entailler</ets>. See <er>Entail</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To settle or fix inalienably on a
person or thing, or on a person and his descendants or a certain line of
descendants; -- said especially of an estate; to bestow as an
heritage.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Allowing them to <qex>entail</qex> their estates.</q>
<rj><qau>Hume.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I here <qex>entail</qex>⟦br⟧
The crown to thee and to thine heirs forever.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To appoint hereditary possessor.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>entail</qex> him and his heirs unto the crown.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To cut or carve in an ornamental way.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Entailed</qex> with curious antics.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Entailment</ent>⟦br⟧
